If GitHub does not provide an Angular option in the built-in templates, you can manually add a `.gitignore` file after creating the repository. Here is the content you can use for the `.gitignore` file:

```plaintext
# dependencies
/node_modules
/.pnp
.pnp.js

# compiled output
/dist
/tmp
/out-tsc

# System files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# Angular specific
.angular
.angular/cache

# IDEs and editors
/.idea
.project
.classpath
.c9/
*.launch
.settings/
*.sublime-workspace

# IDE - VSCode
.vscode/*
!.vscode/settings.json
!.vscode/tasks.json
!.vscode/launch.json
!.vscode/extensions.json

# misc
/.sass-cache
/connect.lock
/coverage
/libpeerconnection.log
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*
testem.log
/typings

# e2e
/e2e/*.js
/e2e/*.map

# Service worker
/ngsw-worker.js

# Environment variables
.env
.env.*
```

1. Create a new file named `.gitignore` in the root of your repository.
2. Copy and paste the above content into the `.gitignore` file.
3. Commit and push the `.gitignore` file to your repository.

This will ensure that the appropriate files and directories are ignored in your Angular project.

